{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":30367,"record_hash":"sha256:b3e5d2efe9895a111b39330041a403f5f315e3b4fbf9c0d9070075bd12e4e9d5","timestamp":"2026-05-11T16:57:36.706Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"assistant","text":"Yes, I think so.\n\nCurrent GitMeta materialization is designed around a metadata ref representing the visible shareable metadata state for that sync lane. For `refs/meta/main`, absence can mean “not present in the current metadata state.”\n\nFor `refs/meta/agentlog`, absence must mean one of two things:\n\n```text\ninside agentlog scope:\n  absent may mean absent/deleted\n\noutside agentlog scope:\n  absent means not part of this ref; leave local data alone\n```\n\nSo GitMeta needs a scoped materialize path that knows the key matcher for the ref it is materializing.\n\nThat likely means adding GitMeta support for a “scope” object, something like:\n\n```rust\nstruct MetaScope {\n    name: \"agentlog\",\n    local_ref: \"refs/meta/local/agentlog\",\n    remote_ref: \"refs/meta/agentlog\",\n    matches_key: fn(&str) -> bool,\n}\n```\n\nThen scoped materialization can:\n\n- parse the remote tree\n- apply additions/updates only for matching keys\n- apply tombstones only for matching keys\n- avoid deleting or overwriting non-matching local keys\n- update scoped sync bookkeeping, not the global/default marker\n\nSo yes: scoped materialization and scoped sync bookkeeping should live in `git-meta`. `but-agentlog` should just say “sync the agentlog scope.”","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-11T16:57:36.706Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"assistant","phase":"final_answer"}}}